%N A272977 Number of ordered ways to write n as x^2 + y^2 + z^2 + w^2 with 3*x^2*y + z^2*w a square, where w is a nonzero integer and x,y,z are nonnegative integers with x >= z.
%C A272977 Conjecture: (i) a(n) > 0 for all n > 0, and a(n) = 1 only for n = 3, 7, 23, 47, 71, 147, 199, 263, 439, 16^k*m (k = 0,1,2,... and m = 6, 12, 24, 44, 56, 140, 156, 174, 204, 284, 4652).
%C A272977 (ii) For each ordered pair (a,b) = (7,1), (8,1), (9,2), any positive integer can be written as x^2 + y^2 + z^2 + w^2 with a*x^2*y + b*z^2*w a square, where x,y,z are nonnegative integers and w is a nonzero integer.
%C A272977 Compare this conjecture with the one in A270073.
%C A272977 See arXiv:1604.06723 for more refinements of Lagrange's four-square theorem.
%H A272977 Zhi-Wei Sun, <a href="/A272977/b272977.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%H A272977 Zhi-Wei Sun, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/1604.06723">Refining Lagrange's four-square theorem</a>, arXiv:1604.06723 [math.GM], 2016.
